<p class="drop-cap">In the beginning, there was no distance between God and humanity. The Eastern Fathers speak of Adam and Eve not as finished products but as infants — freshly created, innocent, brimming with potential, placed in a garden where God walked with them in the cool of the evening. They were made in the <em>image</em> of God and were meant to grow into His <em>likeness</em>. That distinction matters enormously in Eastern theology. The image is a gift. The likeness is a journey.</p>

<p>Creation itself, in this reading, is not merely the stage on which the human drama plays out. It is a participant. "The heavens declare the glory of God," the Psalmist sings, and Eastern Christianity takes this quite literally. The material world is not fallen by nature — it is good, spoken into existence by a God who called it good, saturated with His presence. The Byzantine liturgy still blesses water, bread, wine, oil, and incense — all physical things made holy not by escaping their materiality but by fulfilling it.</p>

<h2>What Happened in the Garden</h2>

<p>Then something went wrong. The story of the Fall in Genesis 3 is one of the most interpreted passages in all of Scripture, and Eastern and Western Christianity have read it quite differently.</p>

<p>In the West — particularly after St. Augustine — the Fall came to be understood primarily in legal terms. Adam sinned, and his guilt passed to all his descendants. Every human being is born carrying Adam's personal guilt. This is the doctrine of <strong>Original Sin</strong> as it developed in the Latin tradition: a stain on the soul, inherited at conception, requiring baptism to remove.</p>

<p>The East never read it that way.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Irenaeus of Lyon, Against Heresies, 2nd century">
  God did not make humanity perfect from the beginning, but susceptible to improvement — like children who must be nourished and grow toward maturity.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Ancestral Sin: Sickness, Not Guilt</h2>

<p>Eastern Christianity speaks not of Original Sin but of <strong>Ancestral Sin</strong>. The difference is more than semantic — it reshapes the entire understanding of what went wrong and what needs to be fixed.</p>

<p>What Adam and Eve passed to their descendants was not <em>guilt</em> but <em>consequences</em>: mortality, a darkened intellect, a weakened will, a tendency toward sin. Think of it less as a courtroom verdict and more as a hereditary illness. A parent who contracts a disease may pass it to their children — but the children are not <em>guilty</em> of having been sick. They are, however, genuinely sick. They need healing.</p>

<p>This is why the Eastern Fathers overwhelmingly use medical language when discussing the Fall. Humanity is not guilty and awaiting sentencing. Humanity is <em>ill</em> and in need of a physician.</p>

