<h2>Gregory of Nyssa and the Garments of Skin</h2>

<p>St. Gregory of Nyssa, one of the great Cappadocian Fathers of the fourth century, offered a reading of the Fall that still shapes Eastern theology. After Adam and Eve disobeyed, God clothed them in "garments of skin" (Genesis 3:21). Gregory understood these garments not merely as physical clothing but as the condition of fallen mortality itself — the heaviness, the passions, the biological drives that now dominate human experience.</p>

<p>But here is the crucial point: the garments are not who we <em>are</em>. Beneath them, the image of God remains intact. It may be obscured, tarnished, buried under layers of mortality and habitual sin — but it is never destroyed. Eastern theology insists on this with remarkable consistency. No matter how far a person falls, the divine image within them is indestructible.</p>

<p>This has practical consequences. If the image of God in each person can never be destroyed, then no human being is beyond hope. No one is totally depraved. The Fall damaged us profoundly, but it did not annihilate what God placed within us at creation.</p>

<h2>Irenaeus and the Childhood of Humanity</h2>

<p>St. Irenaeus of Lyon, writing in the second century, offered perhaps the most distinctive Eastern reading of the Fall. He saw Adam and Eve not as morally perfect adults who catastrophically failed, but as <em>children</em> — newly made, inexperienced, easily deceived. Their sin was real, but it was the sin of immaturity, not of deliberate cosmic rebellion.</p>

<p>This changes the entire emotional register of the story. In the Western telling, the Fall is often presented as a legal catastrophe: a contract broken, a debt incurred, a punishment deserved. In Irenaeus's telling, it is a tragedy of arrested development. Humanity was meant to grow from image to likeness, from infancy to maturity, from creation toward <a href="/glossary/#theosis">theosis</a> — union with God. The Fall interrupted that growth. It did not cancel the destination; it made the journey infinitely harder.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Gregory of Nyssa, On the Making of Man, 4th century">
  The image of God is not lost, but buried — like gold fallen into the mud. It needs only to be uncovered.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Death as the Real Enemy</h2>

<p>If the Fall is understood as sickness rather than guilt, then the primary consequence of the Fall is not <em>condemnation</em> but <em>death</em>. And this is precisely what the Eastern Fathers taught. "The wages of sin is death" (Romans 6:23) — not because God imposed death as a penalty, but because separation from the Source of Life naturally results in dying. Turn a plant away from the sun, and it withers. It is not being punished. It is being deprived of what it needs to live.</p>

<p>This is why the great feast of Eastern Christianity is not Christmas or Good Friday but <strong><a href="/glossary/#pascha">Pascha</a></strong> — the Resurrection. The central drama is not a payment of debt but a defeat of death. Christ enters the tomb and smashes its gates from within. The Anastasis icon — Christ hauling Adam and Eve bodily out of their graves — is the single most important image in Eastern Christianity. It is not an image of forgiveness. It is an image of rescue.</p>

