<h2>Why This Matters Now</h2>

<p>This is not merely an academic distinction. Whether the Fall is understood as guilt or as sickness shapes everything that follows: what salvation means, what the Church does, what the sacraments accomplish, how sin is addressed, what happens after death.</p>

<p>If the problem is guilt, then the solution is a legal transaction — someone paying the penalty. If the problem is sickness, then the solution is a hospital — a community of healing, a physician who enters the illness itself to cure it from within.</p>

<p>Eastern Christianity chose the second metaphor. The Church is a hospital. Sin is a disease. The sacraments are medicine. And Christ is the Physician who became sick so that the sick might be healed.</p>

<p>In the next step, we'll explore what that healing actually looks like — and encounter one of the most extraordinary claims in all of Christian theology: that the goal of human life is not merely to be forgiven, but to become God.</p>

